 anatomically asymmetrical doesn&rsquo;t mean much. What matters is that the feather is <i>aerodynamically</i> asymmetrical, and for this to be the case, the vane asymmetry must be at least three to one&mdash;that is, the trailing blade needs to be three times wider than the leading one. Below this ratio, the feather twists in a destabilizing rather than stabilizing way during flight."},{"type":"embed:image","tag":null,"attributes":{},"content":"","data":{"id":265523,"default_asset_url":"https://static.scientificamerican.com/dam/m/4764d2e5c2426e38/original/saw0524Habi32_m.png","desktop_asset_url":"https://static.scientificamerican.com/dam/m/3b0c2ab046b2fa11/original/saw0524Habi32_d.png","caption":"","credits":"<p>Maria Amorette Klos</p>","contentful_id":"33hgnREIv6d3X1fG5r6oi4","is_published":true,"revision":4,"created_at":"2024-04-04T13:33:04.607000-04:00","updated_at":"2024-04-22T21:31:14.349000-04:00","title":"saw0524Habi32","asset":[{"id":"E6DE10DE-5409-444F-AFA883D4AB192A12","alt":"An illustration shows an aerodynamically asymmetrical feather. The portion above the rachis is one third the height of the portion below the rachis.","url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/4764d2e5c2426e38/original/saw0524Habi32_m.png","data":{"id":"E6DE10DE-5409-444F-AFA883D4AB192A12","url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/media/?mediaId=E6DE10DE-5409-444F-AFA883D4AB192A12","name":"saw0524Habi32_m","tags":[],"type":"image","files":{"mini":{"url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/4764d2e5c2426e38/mini-saw0524Habi32_m.png","width":80,"height":80,"fileSize":null},"original":{"url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/4764d2e5c2426e38/original/saw0524Habi32_m.png","width":1334,"height":543,"fileSize":436789},"webImage":{"url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/4764d2e5c2426e38/webimage-saw0524Habi32_m.png","width":800,"height":326,"fileSize":null},"thumbnail":{"url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/4764d2e5c2426e38/thul-saw0524Habi32_m.png","width":250,"height":102,"fileSize":null}},"width":1334,"height":543,"archive":0,"bra