tent":"Early pennaraptorans such as <i>Microraptor</i> didn&rsquo;t have aerodynamically asymmetrical feathers. But that doesn&rsquo;t mean they couldn&rsquo;t fly. The tendency to twist (whether in a stabilizing or a destabilizing fashion) is only relevant if the feathers are separated enough to do so. Keeping feathers in a wing tip tight and overlapping makes them stable, even if they&rsquo;re not asymmetrical. Asymmetry matters only if the flier spreads its primaries apart in flight like many modern raptors do&mdash;a feature called slotting. So <i>Microraptor</i> and its kin could probably use flapping flight, but their wing shape was necessarily different from that of today&rsquo;s forest-dwelling birds of prey. Specifically, <i>Microraptor</i> had relatively long, narrow wings with tight, unslotted wing tips&mdash;anatomically distinct from the wings of Cooper&rsquo;s Hawks and other modern-day forest hawks but aerodynamically similar."},{"type":"embed:image","tag":null,"attributes":{},"content":"","data":{"id":265524,"default_asset_url":"https://static.scientificamerican.com/dam/m/dbe7694082a39fa/original/saw0524Habi33_m.png","desktop_asset_url":"https://static.scientificamerican.com/dam/m/4651635d39da33e/original/saw0524Habi33_d.png","caption":"","credits":"<p>Maria Amorette Klos</p>","contentful_id":"1gRglaVSCq0hEpOsn1jS5a","is_published":true,"revision":4,"created_at":"2024-04-04T13:34:04.646000-04:00","updated_at":"2024-04-22T21:31:15.023000-04:00","title":"saw0524Habi33","asset":[{"id":"8239C985-7242-47CB-959AE5E8474164AD","alt":"Two illustrations show the difference between a slotted wing and an unslotted wing. In the slotted wing, negative space is visible between feathers at the tip. The unslotted wing does not include negative space.","url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/dbe7694082a39fa/original/saw0524Habi33_m.png","data":{"id":"8239C985-7242-47CB-959AE5E8474164AD","url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/media/?mediaId=8239C985-7242-47CB-959AE5E8474164AD","nam