parates from the wing, causing a precipitous loss of the lift that keeps the bird in the air. It&rsquo;s a vital adaptation that underpins an array of aerial acrobatics."},{"tag":"p","type":"paragraph","attributes":{},"content":"Birds typically need long, narrow wings to soar efficiently&mdash;seabirds such as albatrosses and petrels are perfect examples. The advent of wing-tip slots made it possible to soar with broader wings, paving the way for evolution of a diversity of broad-winged soarers, including vultures and hawks. The aerodynamic advantages of slotting also permit the explosive flight performance of sprinters such as grouses, which spend most of their time on the ground but burst into flight for a short distance when startled. And wing-tip slots provide much greater maneuverability for a wide array of birds that live in forests and other cluttered environments, from songbirds to toucans. In fact, the maneuverability made possible by slotted wings might have helped birds compete with <a href=\\"https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/pterosaurs-were-monsters-of-the-mesozoic-skies/\\">pterosaurs</a> and ultimately survive the end-Cretaceous extinction."},{"tag":"p","type":"paragraph","attributes":{},"content":"<span class=\\"dropcap\\">T</span>he pennaceous feathers we associate with flight aren&rsquo;t the only type of feather birds possess. Feathers in different regions of the body vary in size, shape and function. You can think of feather form as a spectrum, with the large, relatively stiff flight feathers of the wing and tail at one end and the short, fluffy down feathers that sit close to the body at the other. All of them have a central shaft and softer &ldquo;barbs&rdquo; that branch out from the shaft. In flight feathers, the barbs interlock like Velcro teeth to form the smooth, windproof surface of the vanes. In down feathers, the barbs are loosely structured and fluffy to trap heat. Many of the other kinds of feathers combine aspects of these two types. The contour feathers that streamline a bird&rsquo;s body, for example, have vaned tips like flight feathers and noninterlocking barbs like down ones. The bristle feathers that typically occur on the face and may serve protective and sensory purposes meld the flight feathers&rsquo; stiff shafts (called rachises) with the down feathers&rsquo; fluffy base."},{"type":"embed:image","tag":null,"attributes":{},"content":"","data":{"id":265465,"default_asset_url":"https://static.scientificamerican.com/dam/m/6fc46155b309d394/original/sa0524Habi03a.jpg","desktop_asset_url":null,"caption":"<p>The wing of the Greater Prairie-Chicken, a type of grouse, has a slotted tip that helps the bird burst into flight when startled.</p>","credits":"<p>Robert Clark</p>","contentful_id":"2PzrEt05QELYk6vU9VO05f","is_published":true,"revision":5,"created_at":"2024-04-02T16:16:48.468000-04:00","updated_at":"2024-04-22T21:30:31.246000-04:00","title":"sa0524Habi03a","asset":[{"id":"5CE33BC6-605C-4C58-BB08C83FE4897C00","alt":null,"url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/6fc46155b309d394/original/sa0524Habi03a.jpg","data":{"id":"5CE33BC6-605C-4C58-BB08C83FE4897C00","url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/media/?mediaId=5CE33BC6-605C-4C58-BB08C83FE4897C00","name":"sa0524Habi03a","tags":[],"type":"image","files":{"mini":{"url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/6fc46155b309d394/mini-sa0524Habi03a.png","width":80,"height":80,"fileSize":null},"original":{"url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/6fc46155b309d394/original/sa0524Habi03a.jpg","width":4725,"height":3150,"fileSize":4620684},"webImage":{"url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/6fc46155b309d394/webimage-sa0524Habi03a.png","width":800,"height":533,"fileSize":null},"thumbnail":{"url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/6fc46155b309d394/thul-sa0524Habi03a.png","width":250,"height":167,"fileSize":null}},"width":4725,"height":3150,"archive":0,"brandId":"8652EEC0-D205-4C9D-8764853ED3CF88E6","limited":0,"version":1,"fileSize":4620684,"isPublic":1,"original":"https://sciam.bynder.com/