owny hybrid that lets much of the airflow pass through without producing much lift. This arrangement is most likely an adaptation to prevent these feathers from being highly destabilizing. These flashy feathers still increase the cost of flying because they add drag, but that cost may well be less than has been assumed."},{"type":"embed:image","tag":null,"attributes":{},"content":"","data":{"id":265466,"default_asset_url":"https://static.scientificamerican.com/dam/m/7520abb2895e99bb/original/sa0524Habi04a.jpg","desktop_asset_url":null,"caption":"<p>The Barn Owl&lsquo;s primary feathers have features that allow this bird of prey to fly silently.</p>","credits":"<p>Robert Clark</p>","contentful_id":"4h2Jvakeuu24iFyEIvVULN","is_published":true,"revision":5,"created_at":"2024-04-02T16:18:17.006000-04:00","updated_at":"2024-04-22T21:30:32.033000-04:00","title":"sa0524Habi04a","asset":[{"id":"02CC135A-E9D1-475E-88009BE02349B0EA","alt":null,"url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/7520abb2895e99bb/original/sa0524Habi04a.jpg","data":{"id":"02CC135A-E9D1-475E-88009BE02349B0EA","url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/media/?mediaId=02CC135A-E9D1-475E-88009BE02349B0EA","name":"sa0524Habi04a","tags":[],"type":"image","files":{"mini":{"url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/7520abb2895e99bb/mini-sa0524Habi04a.png","width":80,"height":80,"fileSize":null},"original":{"url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/7520abb2895e99bb/original/sa0524Habi04a.jpg","width":2377,"height":3566,"fileSize":2520050},"webImage":{"url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/7520abb2895e99bb/webimage-sa0524Habi04a.png","width":400,"height":600,"fileSize":null},"thumbnail":{"url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/7520abb2895e99bb/thul-sa0524Habi04a.png","width":167,"height":250,"fileSize":null}},"width":2377,"height":3566,"archive":0,"brandId":"8652EEC0-D205-4C9D-8764853ED3CF88E6","limited":0,"version":1,"fileSize":2520050,"isPublic":1,"original":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/7520abb2895e99bb/original/sa0524Habi04a.jpg","copyright":null,"extension":