 landing was enough for him to pounce on it perfectly. (Readers may also find solace in knowing that he still flew, having memorized his enclosure, and was regularly taken around for walks and neck scratches.)"},{"tag":"p","type":"paragraph","attributes":{},"content":"Still, that exceptional sense of <a href=\\"https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/the-hearing-of-the-barn-owl/\\">hearing</a> wouldn&rsquo;t get owls very far without some additional feather adaptations. Other nocturnal creatures can also hear very well, and an owl whose feathers were rustling in flight would be hard-pressed to get close to its vigilant prey. Furthermore, owls might not hear quietly creeping prey if their own feather sounds covered the faint noises of their targets. Owls solved both problems by evolving feather traits that make them inaudible during flight."},{"type":"embed:image","tag":null,"attributes":{},"content":"","data":{"id":265467,"default_asset_url":"https://static.scientificamerican.com/dam/m/8fdd7427da2026d/original/sa0524Habi05.jpg","desktop_asset_url":null,"caption":"<p>The extremely stiff feathers of hummingbirds such as Anna&rsquo;s Hummingbird help to support their distinctive, hovering flight.</p>","credits":"<p>Kathleen Reeder Wildlife Photography/Getty Images</p>","contentful_id":"3RUNPCXQVAknjGwzHuqwKN","is_published":true,"revision":5,"created_at":"2024-04-02T16:20:05.786000-04:00","updated_at":"2024-04-22T21:30:32.675000-04:00","title":"sa0524Habi05","asset":[{"id":"D81360C2-0C2D-43C1-BCAE52A0AC32CFFC","alt":null,"url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/8fdd7427da2026d/original/sa0524Habi05.jpg","data":{"id":"D81360C2-0C2D-43C1-BCAE52A0AC32CFFC","url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/media/?mediaId=D81360C2-0C2D-43C1-BCAE52A0AC32CFFC","name":"sa0524Habi05","tags":[],"type":"image","files":{"mini":{"url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/8fdd7427da2026d/mini-sa0524Habi05.png","width":80,"height":80,"fileSize":null},"original":{"url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/8fdd7427da2026d/or