st enough air to provide some insulation without making the penguin buoyant, supplementing the fat layer that helps to keep the bird warm."},{"tag":"p","type":"paragraph","attributes":{},"content":"In the absence of any constraints posed by flight, penguins jettisoned the more typical feather accoutrements of their ancestors in favor of a novel suit of drag-&shy;&shy;reducing, minimum-buoyancy feathers. These feathers are a key part of the package of adaptations that have made penguins the undisputed diving champions of the avian world, capable of reaching depths of more than 1,600 feet in search of krill, fish, and other aquatic prey."},{"type":"embed:image","tag":null,"attributes":{},"content":"","data":{"id":265530,"default_asset_url":"https://static.scientificamerican.com/dam/m/7e3a58790ccdbdc2/original/saw0524Habi38_m.png","desktop_asset_url":"https://static.scientificamerican.com/dam/m/374747127ebbdcf5/original/saw0524Habi38_d.png","caption":"","credits":"<p>Maria Amorette Klos</p>","contentful_id":"2mjpZTDT9UjP8Th5qagPY6","is_published":true,"revision":4,"created_at":"2024-04-04T13:39:13.633000-04:00","updated_at":"2024-04-22T21:31:19.853000-04:00","title":"saw0524Habi38","asset":[{"id":"ACF0D590-7186-4159-98242D5B7E85BD37","alt":"An illustration of a penguin is accompanied by several feather details. Densely packed feathers on the penguin’s back traps a thin layer of water near the bird.","url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/7e3a58790ccdbdc2/original/saw0524Habi38_m.png","data":{"id":"ACF0D590-7186-4159-98242D5B7E85BD37","url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/media/?mediaId=ACF0D590-7186-4159-98242D5B7E85BD37","name":"saw0524Habi38_m","tags":[],"type":"image","files":{"mini":{"url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/7e3a58790ccdbdc2/mini-saw0524Habi38_m.png","width":80,"height":80,"fileSize":null},"original":{"url":"https://sciam.bynder.com/m/7e3a58790ccdbdc2/original/saw0524Habi38_m.png","width":1334,"height":1870,"fileSize":1622782},"webImage":{"url":"https://sciam.bynder.